As the commentary assumes that the reader is at a somewhat advanced point in his Latin studies, little attention is paid to the commonplaces of grammar 3 on the other hand, consider- able prominence is given to the idiosyncracies of Tacitus' Latinity, and to the changes which the language had under- gone since the Ciceronian period. A leading aim in the com- mentary is to present a connected view of the character and reign of Tiberius, and to trace the constitutional and adminis- trative changes which took place under that emperor. To make the view more complete, the lost portions of the fifth and sixth Books have been, in a measure, supplied by extracts . from Dio CassiuS, Suetonius, and Juvenal.

The long and concentrated study of Tacitus has accumulated a rich store of illustrative material that is now the common property of scholarship. This material has been freely used for the present edition 3 but special acknowledgment is due for aid derived from the editions of Furneaux (Clarendon PreSS‚ Oxford‚ 1884), Nipperdey (8th edition, by Andresen, Berlin, 1884), Drager (4th edition, Leipsic‚ 1882), and Pfitzner (Gotha, 1884), and also from Drager's Syntax und Stil des Tacitus (3'd ed„ LeipsiC‚ 1882), and Gerber and Greef's Lexicon Taciteum (A-M., Leipsic‚ 1877—88). In the discussion of constitu- tional and antiquarian questions Mommsen's labors have been of great service3 Marquardt and Madvig have also been fre- quently consulted.
